\details{
\strong{What changes vs. \code{grf::causal_forest()}?} Only the nuisance
predictions used to centre \code{Y} and \code{W}. The CATE estimator, honesty
splits, and identification assumptions are inherited from \pkg{grf}.

\strong{Why cv.glmnet?} Penalized regression is a fast, well-understood
baseline for nuisance estimation in Robinson-style residualisation
(Chernozhukov et al., 2018, treat lasso/elastic-net nuisances as the
canonical DML first stage).

\strong{Linearity-in-X assumption (load-bearing).} \code{glmcf()} fits cv.glmnet
on \code{X} as supplied, so \code{Y.hat} and \code{W.hat} are linear in the columns
of \code{X} (with elastic-net penalty + optional relax). If the true
\code{m(x) = E[Y | X]} or \code{e(x) = E[W | X]} is non-linear in \code{X}, the
lasso residuals carry residual confounding correlated with \code{X}, which
biases the Robinson centering and propagates into the CATE estimates
downstream. \pkg{grf}'s residual-on-residual splits absorb some of
this but not all. \strong{For non-linear nuisances, pre-transform \code{X}
(interactions, splines, polynomials) before passing to \code{glmcf()}, or
use \code{\link[=tabcf]{tabcf()}} which handles non-linearity natively.}

\strong{DML rate requirement for downstream inference.} For valid
sqrt(n) inference from \code{grf::average_treatment_effect()} (and
similar), DML theory requires both nuisances to converge at
\code{o(n^{-1/4})}. Lasso achieves
\code{s_n * sqrt(log(p) / n)} under approximate sparsity (effective
sparsity \code{s_n}, ambient dimension \code{p}). At small \code{p} and sparse
signal this is satisfied; at moderate \code{p} (e.g. \code{p > sqrt(n)}) or
non-sparse signal it is \strong{not}, and ATE confidence intervals from
\code{grf} will under-cover. If you are in a wide-X / non-sparse regime,
prefer \code{\link[=tabcf]{tabcf()}} or random-forest nuisances.

\strong{Cross-fitting.} Predictions are produced via K-fold cross-fitting:
for each fold, \code{cv.glmnet()} is fit on the other \code{K - 1} folds and
predicts on the held-out fold. If \code{c.forest$clusters} is non-trivial,
folds are built so that all units in a cluster end up in the same
fold (preserving \pkg{grf}'s cluster-aware inference).

\strong{Treatment type.} \code{W} is treated as binary if it is \verb{\{0, 1\}}-valued
(numeric or integer with both levels present), a logical, or a 2-level
factor; in that case \code{family = "binomial"} is used and predictions are
clipped to \verb{[eps, 1 - eps]} to preserve overlap. Otherwise \code{W} is
treated as continuous and \code{family = "gaussian"} is used. If \code{W} is
numeric with exactly 2 unique values that are not \verb{\{0, 1\}} (e.g.
\verb{\{1, 2\}} or \verb{\{-1, 1\}}), \code{glmcf()} emits a warning and falls back to
the gaussian regressor; encode such treatments as \code{0/1} to use the
classifier.

\strong{Alpha tuning and reproducibility.} Within each cross-fit fold,
the inner CV is run with a single shared \code{foldid} across all candidate
alphas so the minimum-CV-deviance comparison across alphas is on the
same splits. The selected alpha may differ across folds and between
Y and W. Per-fold reselection is consistent in rate but
data-dependent: at small \code{n_train}, differences in CV deviance across
alphas are within sampling error, so the selected alpha can vary
under resampling (the actual selections are recorded in
\code{attr(out, "glmcf_meta")$alpha_y} and \verb{$alpha_w} for diagnostics).
For studies that need reproducible CIs under resampling (bootstrap,
Monte Carlo), prefer a single fixed alpha (e.g. \code{alpha = 1} for pure
lasso) over the default grid.

\strong{Sample weights.} \code{c.forest$sample.weights} are passed to
\code{cv.glmnet()} via the \code{weights} argument so that weighted training is
consistent between the nuisance fits and the downstream causal forest.

\strong{Dependencies.} The \code{glmnet} package is gated as a Suggests
dependency. \code{glmcf()} calls \code{rlang::check_installed("glmnet")} at the
top and raises an informative error if missing.
}
